<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41907982</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>30</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>30</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0973-2063</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>21</Volume><Issue>12</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Bioinformation</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Bioinformation</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Fall risk after total hip replacement: A functional correlation study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>4706</StartPage><EndPage>4710</EndPage><MedlinePgn>4706-4710</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.6026/973206300214706</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Falls are a common issue among older adults after total hip arthroplasty (THA), with factors such as reduced mobility and fear of falling contributing. Therefore, it is of interest to examine recovery and fall-related concerns in patients following total hip arthroplasty (THA). It used measures such as the Harris Hip Score (HHS) and the Falls Efficacy Scale (FES) to assess progress. The study found that the Sit-to-Stand test (STS) was strongly linked to fall confidence, emphasising its value in monitoring recovery and fall risk. This study is the identification of key functional measures (such as the Sit-to-Stand test and Falls Efficacy Scale) in assessing recovery and fall risk in older adults post-total hip arthroplasty, emphasizing the role of physical and psychological factors in improving fall-related confidence and mobility.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2025 Biomedical Informatics.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Agnihotri</LastName><ForeName>Manoj</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Musculoskeletal Ph